# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hertz
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] In 2019, four of the seven SI base units specified in the International System of Quantities were redefined in terms of natural physical constants, rather than human artefacts such as the standard kilogram.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] The second, metre, and candela had previously been redefined using physical constants.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] The four new definitions aimed to improve the SI without changing the value of any units, ensuring continuity with existing measurements.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] In November 2018, the 26th General Conference on Weights and Measures (CGPM) unanimously approved these changes, which the International Committee for Weights and Measures (CIPM) had proposed earlier that year after determining that previously agreed conditions for the change had been met.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] These conditions were satisfied by a series of experiments that measured the constants to high accuracy relative to the old SI definitions, and were the culmination of decades of research.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] The previous major change of the metric system occurred in 1960 when the International System of Units (SI) was formally published.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] At this time the metre was redefined: the definition was changed from the prototype of the metre to a certain number of wavelengths of a spectral line of a krypton-86 radiation, making it derivable from universal natural phenomena.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] The kilogram remained defined by a physical prototype, leaving it the only artefact upon which the SI unit definitions depended.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] At this time the SI, as a coherent system, was constructed around seven *base units*, powers of which were used to construct all other units.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] With the 2019 redefinition, the SI is constructed around seven defining *constants*, allowing all units to be constructed directly from these constants.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] The designation of base units is retained but is no longer essential to define the SI units.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] The metric system was originally conceived as a system of measurement that was derivable from unchanging phenomena, but practical limitations necessitated the use of artefacts – the prototype of the metre and prototype of the kilogram – when the metric system was introduced in France in 1799.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] The definitions of some units were defined by measurements that are difficult to precisely realise in a laboratory, such as the kelvin, which was defined in terms of the triple point of water.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] With the 2019 redefinition, the SI became wholly derivable from natural phenomena with most units being based on fundamental physical constants.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] A number of authors have published criticisms of the revised definitions; their criticisms include the premise that the proposal failed to address the impact of breaking the link between the definition of the dalton and the definitions of the kilogram, the mole, and the Avogadro constant.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] The basic structure of the SI was developed over about 170 years between 1791 and 1960.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] Since 1960, technological advances have made it possible to address weaknesses in the SI such as the dependence on a physical artefact to define the kilogram.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] During the early years of the French Revolution, the leaders of the French National Constituent Assembly decided to introduce a new system of measurement that was based on the principles of logic and natural phenomena.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] The metre was defined as one ten-millionth of the distance from the north pole to the equator and the kilogram as the mass of one thousandth of a cubic metre of pure water.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] Although these definitions were chosen to avoid ownership of the units, they could not be measured with sufficient convenience or precision to be of practical use.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] Instead, realisations were created in the form of the **mètre des Archives** and **kilogramme des Archives**, which were a "best attempt" at fulfilling these principles.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] The 1st CGPM (1889) formally approved the use of 40 prototype metres and 40 prototype kilograms made by the British firm Johnson Matthey as the standards mandated by the Convention of the Metre.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] 6 and Kilogram KIII were designated as the international prototype of the metre and the kilogram, respectively; the CGPM retained other copies as working copies, and the rest were distributed to member states for use as their national prototypes.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] About once every 40 years, the national prototypes were compared with and recalibrated against the international prototype.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] In 1921 the Convention of the Metre was revised and the mandate of the CGPM was extended to provide standards for all units of measure, not just mass and length.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] In the ensuing years, the CGPM took on responsibility for providing standards of electrical current (1946), luminosity (1946), temperature (1948), time (1956), and molar mass (1971).
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] The 9th CGPM in 1948 instructed the CIPM "to make recommendations for a single practical system of units of measurement, suitable for adoption by all countries adhering to the Metre Convention".
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] The recommendations based on this mandate were presented to the 11th CGPM (1960), where they were formally accepted and given the name "**Système International d'Unités**" and its abbreviation "SI".
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] The 17th CGPM (1983) replaced the 1960 definition of the metre with one based on the second by giving an exact definition of the speed of light in units of metres per second.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] Since their manufacture, drifts of up to 2×10−8 kilograms (20 μg) per year in the national prototype kilograms relative to the international prototype of the kilogram (IPK) have been detected.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] There was no way of determining whether the national prototypes were gaining mass or whether the IPK was losing mass.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] Newcastle University metrologist Peter Cumpson has since identified mercury vapour absorption or carbonaceous contamination as possible causes of this drift.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] At the 21st meeting of the CGPM (1999), national laboratories were urged to investigate ways of breaking the link between the kilogram and a specific artefact.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] Metrologists investigated several alternative approaches to redefining the kilogram based on fundamental physical constants.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] Among others, the Avogadro project and the development of the Kibble balance (known as the "watt balance" before 2016) promised methods of indirectly measuring mass with very high precision.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] These projects provided tools that enable alternative means of redefining the kilogram.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] A report published in 2007 by the Consultative Committee for Thermometry (CCT) to the CIPM noted that their current definition of temperature has proved to be unsatisfactory for temperatures below 20 K and for temperatures above 1300 K.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] The committee took the view that the Boltzmann constant provided a better basis for temperature measurement than did the triple point of water because it overcame these difficulties.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] At its 23rd meeting (2007), the CGPM mandated the CIPM to investigate the use of natural constants as the basis for all units of measure rather than the artefacts that were then in use.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] The following year this was endorsed by the International Union of Pure and Applied Physics (IUPAP).
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] At a meeting of the CCU held in Reading, United Kingdom, in September 2010, a resolution and draft changes to the SI brochure that were to be presented to the next meeting of the CIPM in October 2010 were agreed to in principle.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] The CIPM meeting of October 2010 found "the conditions set by the General Conference at its 23rd meeting have not yet been fully met.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] For this reason the CIPM does not propose a revision of the SI at the present time".
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] The CIPM, however, presented a resolution for consideration at the 24th CGPM (17–21 October 2011) to agree to the new definitions in principle, but not to implement them until the details had been finalised.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] This resolution was accepted by the conference, and in addition the CGPM moved the date of the 25th meeting forward from 2015 to 2014.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] At the 25th meeting on 18 to 20 November 2014, it was found that "despite [progress in the necessary requirements] the data do not yet appear to be sufficiently robust for the CGPM to adopt the revised SI at its 25th meeting", thus postponing the revision to the next meeting in 2018.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] Measurements accurate enough to meet the conditions were available in 2017 and the redefinition was adopted at the 26th CGPM (13–16 November 2018).
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] Following the successful 1983 redefinition of the metre in terms of an exact numerical value for the speed of light, the BIPM's Consultative Committee for Units (CCU) recommended and the BIPM proposed that four further constants of nature should be defined to have exact values.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] As part of the redefinition, the International Prototype of the Kilogram was retired and definitions of the kilogram, the ampere, and the kelvin were replaced.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] These changes have the effect of redefining the SI base units, though the definitions of the SI derived units in terms of the base units remain the same.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] Following the CCU proposal, the texts of the definitions of all of the base units were either refined or rewritten, changing the emphasis from explicit-unit-type to explicit-constant-type definitions.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] Explicit-unit definitions define a unit in terms of a specific example of that unit; for example, in 1324 Edward II defined the inch as being the length of three barleycorns, and from 1889 to 2019 the kilogram was defined as the mass of the International Prototype of the kilogram.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] In explicit-constant definitions, a constant of nature is given a specified value, and the definition of the unit emerges as a consequence; for example, in 2019, the speed of light was defined as exactly 299792458 metres per second.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] The length of the metre could be derived because the second had been already independently defined.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] The previous and 2019 definitions are given below.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] The new definition of the second is effectively the same as the previous one, the only difference being that the conditions under which the definition applies are more rigorously defined.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] The new definition of the metre is effectively the same as the previous one, the only difference being that the additional rigour in the definition of the second propagated to the metre.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] The definition of the kilogram fundamentally changed from an artefact (the International Prototype of the Kilogram) to a constant of nature.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] Because the Planck constant relates photon energy to photon frequency, the new definition relates the kilogram to the mass equivalent of the energy of a photon at a specific frequency.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] The definition of the ampere underwent a major revision.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] For illustration, this is equivalent to defining one coulomb to be an exact specified multiple of the elementary charge.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] Because the previous definition contains a reference to force, which has the dimensions MLT−2, it follows that in the previous SI the kilogram, metre, and second – the base units representing these dimensions – had to be defined before the ampere could be defined.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] Other consequences of the previous definition were that in SI the value of vacuum permeability (*μ*0) was fixed at exactly 4*π*×10−7 H⋅m−1.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] A consequence of the revised definition is that the ampere no longer depends on the definitions of the kilogram and the metre; it does, however, still depend on the definition of the second.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] In addition, the numerical values when expressed in SI units of the vacuum permeability, vacuum permittivity, and impedance of free space, which were exact before the redefinition, are subject to experimental error after the redefinition.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] For example, the numerical value of the vacuum permeability has a relative uncertainty equal to that of the experimental value of the fine-structure constant $\alpha$ .
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] The CODATA 2018 value for the relative standard uncertainty of $\alpha$ is 1.6×10−10.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] The definition of the kelvin underwent a fundamental change.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] Rather than using the triple point of water to fix the temperature scale, the new definition uses the energy equivalent as given by Boltzmann's equation.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] The previous definition of the mole linked it to the kilogram.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] The revised definition breaks that link by making a mole a specific number of entities of the substance in question.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] One consequence of this change is that the previously defined relationship between the mass of the 12C atom, the dalton, the kilogram, and the Avogadro constant is no longer exact.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] The wording of the 9th SI Brochure implies that the first statement remains valid, which means the second is no longer exactly true.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] The molar mass constant, while still with great accuracy remaining 1 g/mol, is no longer exactly equal to that.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] The new definition of the candela is effectively the same as the previous definition as dependent on other base units, with the result that the redefinition of the kilogram and the additional rigour in the definitions of the second and metre propagate to the candela.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] All seven of the SI base units are defined in terms of defined constants and universal physical constants.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] Seven constants are needed to define the seven base units but there is not a direct correspondence between each specific base unit and a specific constant; except the second and the mole, more than one of the seven constants contributes to the definition of any given base unit.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] When the New SI was first designed, there were more than six suitable physical constants from which the designers could choose.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] For example, once length and time had been established, the universal gravitational constant *G* could, from a dimensional point of view, be used to define mass.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] The physical constants were chosen on the basis of minimal uncertainty associated with measuring the constant and the degree of independence of the constant in respect of other constants that were being used.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] Much of the work done by the CIPM is delegated to consultative committees.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] The CIPM Consultative Committee for Units (CCU) has made the proposed changes while other committees have examined the proposal in detail and have made recommendations regarding their acceptance by the CGPM in 2014.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] As of March 2011, the International Avogadro Coordination (IAC) group had obtained an uncertainty of 3.0×10−8 and NIST had obtained an uncertainty of 3.6×10−8 in their measurements.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] On 1 September 2012 the European Association of National Metrology Institutes (EURAMET) launched a formal project to reduce the relative difference between the Kibble balance and the silicon sphere approach to measuring the kilogram from (17±5)×10−8 to within 2×10−8.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] As of the 2014 CODATA-recommended values of the fundamental physical constants published in 2016 using data collected until the end of 2014, all measurements met the CGPM's requirements, and the redefinition and the next CGPM quadrennial meeting in late 2018 could now proceed.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] The vote, which was held on 16 November 2018 at the 26th CGPM, was unanimous; all attending national representatives voted in favour of the revised proposal.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] The new definitions became effective on 20 May 2019.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] The changes proposed in the new SI only addressed problems with the definition of the base units, including new definitions of the candela and the mole – units Foster argued are not true base units.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] Other issues raised by Foster fell outside the scope of the proposal.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] Concerns have been expressed that the use of explicit-constant definitions of the unit being defined that are not related to an example of its quantity will have many adverse effects.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] When the scale of the divergence between the IPK and national kilogram prototypes was reported in 2005, a debate began about whether the kilogram should be defined in terms of the mass of the silicon-28 atom or by using the Kibble balance.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] If the mass of a silicon atom were to be determined by the Avogadro project using the Avogadro constant, it could be linked directly to the kilogram.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] Concerns that the authors of the proposal had failed to address the impact of breaking the link between the mole, kilogram, dalton, and the Avogadro constant (*N*A) have also been expressed.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] This direct link has caused many to argue that the mole is not a true physical unit but, according to the Swedish philosopher Johansson, a "scaling factor".
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] The 8th edition of the SI Brochure defined the dalton in terms of the mass of an atom of 12C.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] It defined the Avogadro constant in terms of this mass and the kilogram, making it determined by experiment.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] The redefinition fixes the Avogadro constant and the 9th SI Brochure retains the definition of dalton in terms of 12C, with the effect that the link between the dalton and the kilogram will be broken.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] In 1993, the International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry (IUPAC) approved the use of the dalton as an alternative name for the unified atomic mass unit with the qualification that the CGPM had not given its approval.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] This would result in the dalton and the atomic mass unit potentially differing from each other with a relative uncertainty of the order of 10−10.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] The 9th SI Brochure, however, defines both the dalton (Da) and the unified atomic mass unit (u) as exactly ⁠1/12⁠ of the mass of a free carbon-12 atom and not in relation to the kilogram, with the effect that the above equation will be inexact.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] Different temperature ranges need different measurement methods.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] Room temperature can be measured by means of expansion and contraction of a liquid in a thermometer but high temperatures are often associated with colour of blackbody radiation.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] Chyla, approaching the structure of SI from a philosophical point of view in the *Journal of the Polish Physical Society*, argued that temperature is not a real base unit but is an average of the thermal energies of the individual particles that comprise the body concerned.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] Chyla acknowledged, however, that in the macroscopic world, temperature plays the role of a base unit because much of the theory of thermodynamics is based on temperature.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] The Consultative Committee for Thermometry, part of the International Committee for Weights and Measures, publishes a *mise en pratique* (practical technique), last updated in 1990, for measuring temperature.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] At very low and at very high temperatures it often links energy to temperature via the Boltzmann constant.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] Foster argued that "luminous intensity [the candela] is not a physical quantity, but a photobiological quantity that exists in human perception", questioning whether the candela should be a base unit.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] Before the 1979 decision to define photometric units in terms of luminous flux (power) rather than luminous intensities of standard light sources, there was already doubt whether there should still be a separate base unit for photometry.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] Furthermore, there was unanimous agreement that the lumen was now more fundamental than the candela.
[src:hertz/2019-revision-of-the-si] However, for the sake of continuity the candela was kept as base unit.
[src:hertz/adult] An **adult** is an animal that has reached full growth.
[src:hertz/adult] The biological definition of *adult* is an organism that has reached sexual maturity and thus capable of reproduction.
[src:hertz/adult] In the human context, the term *adult* has meanings associated with legal and social concepts.
[src:hertz/adult] In contrast to a non-adult or "minor", a **legal adult** is a person who has attained the age of majority and is therefore regarded as independent, self-sufficient, and responsible.
[src:hertz/adult] The typical age of attaining adulthood for humans is 18 years, although definition may vary by country.
[src:hertz/adult] A person may be physically mature and a biological adult by age 16 or so, but not defined as an adult by law until older ages.
[src:hertz/adult] For example, in the US, one cannot join the armed forces or vote until age 18, and one cannot take on many legal and financial responsibilities until age 21.
[src:hertz/adult] Human adulthood encompasses psychological adult development.
[src:hertz/adult] Definitions of adulthood are often inconsistent and contradictory; a person may be biologically an adult, and have adult behavior, but still be treated as a child if they are under the legal age of majority.
[src:hertz/adult] Conversely, one may legally be an adult but possess none of the maturity and responsibility that may define an adult character.
[src:hertz/adult] In different cultures, there are events that relate passing from being a child to becoming an adult or coming of age.
[src:hertz/adult] This often encompasses passing a series of tests to demonstrate that a person is prepared for adulthood, or reaching a specified age, sometimes in conjunction with demonstrating preparation.
[src:hertz/adult] Most modern societies determine legal adulthood based on reaching a legally specified age without requiring a demonstration of physical maturity or preparation for adulthood.
[src:hertz/adult] In the past, a person usually moved from the status of child directly to the status of adult, often with this shift being marked by some type of coming-of-age test or ceremony.
[src:hertz/adult] During the Industrial Revolution, children went to work as soon as they could in order to help provide for their family.
[src:hertz/adult] There was not a huge emphasis on school or education in general.
[src:hertz/adult] Many children could get a job and were not required to have experience as adults are nowadays.
[src:hertz/adult] In recent years, studies of adulthood have identified characteristic traits that go far beyond mere physical maturity.
[src:hertz/adult] These markers for a full, mentally developed, adult include traits of personal responsibilities in multiple aspects of life.
[src:hertz/adult] Although few or no established dictionaries provide a definition for the two-word term *biological adult*, the first definition of *adult* in multiple dictionaries includes "the stage of the life cycle of an animal after reproductive capacity has been attained".
[src:hertz/adult] Thus, the base definition of the word *adult* is the period beginning at physical sexual maturity, which occurs sometime after the onset of puberty.
[src:hertz/adult] Although this is the primary definition of the base word "adult", the term is also frequently used to refer to social adults.
[src:hertz/adult] The two-word term *biological adult* stresses or clarifies that the original definition, based on physical maturity (i.e. having reached reproductive competency), is being used.
[src:hertz/adult] The time of puberty varies from child to child, but usually begins between 10 and 12 years old.
[src:hertz/adult] Girls typically begin the process of puberty at age 10 or 11, and boys at age 11 or 12.
[src:hertz/adult] Girls generally complete puberty by 15–17, and boys by age 16 or 17.
[src:hertz/adult] Nutrition, genetics and environment also usually play a part in the onset of puberty.
[src:hertz/adult] Girls will go through a growth spurt and gain weight in several areas of their body.
[src:hertz/adult] Boys will go through similar spurts in growth, though it is usually not in a similar style or time frame.
[src:hertz/adult] This is due to the natural processes of puberty, but genetics also plays a part in how much weight they gain or how much taller they get.
[src:hertz/adult] One recent area of debate within the science of brain development is the most likely chronological age for full mental maturity, or indeed, if such an age even exists.
[src:hertz/adult] Common claims repeated in the media since 2005 (based upon interpretations of imaging data) have commonly suggested an "end-point" of age 25, referring to the prefrontal cortex as one area that is not yet fully mature at the age of 18.
[src:hertz/adult] Legally, *adulthood* typically means that one has reached the age of majority – when parents lose parental rights and responsibilities regarding the person concerned.
[src:hertz/adult] Admission of a young person to a place may be restricted because of danger for that person, concern that the place may lead the person to immoral behavior, or because of the risk that the young person causes damage (for example, at an exhibition of fragile items).
[src:hertz/adult] One can distinguish the legality of acts of a young person, or of enabling a young person to carry out that act, by selling, renting out, showing, permitting entrance, allowing participation, etc.
[src:hertz/adult] There may be distinction between commercially and socially enabling.
[src:hertz/adult] Sometimes there is the requirement of supervision by a legal guardian, or just by an adult.
[src:hertz/adult] Sometimes there is no requirement, but rather a recommendation.
[src:hertz/adult] The age of majority ranges internationally from ages 15 to 21, with 18 being the most common age.
[src:hertz/adult] Nigeria, Mali, Democratic Republic of Congo and Cameroon define adulthood at age 15, but marriage of girls at an earlier age is common.
[src:hertz/adult] The legal age of adulthood in Nebraska and Alabama in the United States is 19.
[src:hertz/adult] The legal age of adulthood in South Korea is 19.
[src:hertz/adult] The legal age of adulthood in Mississippi and Puerto Rico in the U.S. and Bahrain is 21.
[src:hertz/adult] Prior to the 1970s, young people were not classed as adults until 21 in most western nations.
[src:hertz/adult] For example, in the United States, young citizens could not vote in many elections until 21 until July 1971 when the 26th Amendment passed mandating that the right to vote cannot be abridged for anyone 18 or older.
[src:hertz/adult] The voting age was lowered in response to the fact that young men between the ages of 18 and 21 were drafted into the army to fight in the Vietnam War, hence the popular slogan "old enough to fight, old enough to vote".
[src:hertz/adult] Young people under 21 in the US could also not purchase alcohol, purchase handguns, sign a binding contract, or marry without permission from parents.
[src:hertz/adult] After the voting age was lowered, many states also moved to lower the drinking age (with most states having a minimum age of 18 or 19) and also to lower the age of legal majority (adulthood) to 18.
[src:hertz/adult] However, there are legal activities where 18 is not the default age of adulthood.
[src:hertz/adult] There are still some exceptions where 21 (or even higher) is still the benchmark for certain rights or responsibilities.
[src:hertz/adult] This was done in response to reducing the number of drunk driving fatalities prevalent among young drivers.
[src:hertz/adult] States that choose not to comply can lose up to 10% of highway funding.
[src:hertz/adult] The Credit Card Act of 2009 imposed tougher safeguards for young adults between the ages of 18 and 20 obtaining a credit card.
[src:hertz/adult] Young adults under the age of 21 must either have a co-signer 21 or older or show proof (usually a source of income) that they can repay their credit card balance.
[src:hertz/adult] Unless that requirement is met, one must wait until 21 to be approved for a credit card on their own.
[src:hertz/adult] The Affordable Care Act of 2010 expands the age that young adults can remain on their parent's health insurance plan up to age 26.
[src:hertz/adult] As of December 2019, the federal government raised the legal age to purchase tobacco and vaping products from 18 to 21.
[src:hertz/adult] In states where recreational marijuana is legalized, the default age is also 21, though those younger may be able to obtain medical marijuana prescriptions or cards upon seeing a physician.
[src:hertz/adult] Gambling also varies from 18 to 21 depending on the state and many rental car companies do not rent cars to those under 21 and have surcharges for drivers under 25 (although this is not codified, and is company policy).
[src:hertz/adult] This comes at a time when there are ongoing debates about whether those between 18 and 20 should be exempted from the death penalty.
[src:hertz/adult] In Germany, courts largely sentence defendants under the age of 21 according to juvenile law in a bid to help them reintegrate into society and mete out punishments that fit the crime as well as the offender.
[src:hertz/adult] In May 2021, the state of Texas raised the age that one can be an exotic dancer and work and patronize sexually oriented businesses from 18 to 21.
[src:hertz/adult] In the UK, there have been many proposals to raise the age that one can buy tobacco from 18 to 21 in an attempt to curb teen and young adult use to get to a "smoke-free" UK by 2030.
[src:hertz/adult] At the same time, however, even though the generally accepted age of majority is 18 in most nations, there are rights or privileges afforded to adolescents who have not yet reached legal adulthood.
[src:hertz/adult] In the United States, youth are able to get a part-time job at 14 provided they have a work permit.
[src:hertz/adult] At 16, one is able to obtain a driver's permit or license depending on state laws and is able to work most jobs (except ones requiring heavy machinery) and consent to sexual activity (depending on the state).
[src:hertz/adult] At 17, one is able to enlist in the armed forces with parental consent although they cannot be deployed to be in combat roles until age 18.
[src:hertz/adult] The voting age for local elections in most American cities is 18.
[src:hertz/adult] But in five localities nationwide — four of which are in Maryland — 16 and 17-year-olds are eligible to vote.
[src:hertz/adult] The cities are Takoma Park, Riverdale, Greenbelt, and Hyattsville.
[src:hertz/adult] In 2020, students 16 or older in Oakland, California gained the right to vote in school board elections.
[src:hertz/adult] There is a growing movement to lower the voting age in the US and many other countries from 18 to 16 in hopes of engaging the youth vote and encouraging greater electoral participation.
[src:hertz/adult] Some countries already have a voting age of 16 which include Austria, Scotland, Argentina, Brazil, Wales, Cuba, and Ecuador.
[src:hertz/adult] In Germany, one can purchase beer and wine at the age of 16 although they cannot purchase spirits or hard liquor until 18.
[src:hertz/adult] The age of consent in Germany is 14 if both partners are under 18.
[src:hertz/adult] Sexual activity with a person under 18 is punishable if the adult is a person of authority over the minor in upbringing, education, care, or employment.
[src:hertz/adult] In contrast to biological perspectives of aging and adulthood, social scientists conceptualize adulthood as socially constructed.
[src:hertz/adult] While aging is an established biological process, the attainment of adulthood is social in its criteria.
[src:hertz/adult] In contrast to other perspectives that conceptualize aging and the attainment of adulthood as a largely universal development, regardless of context, nation, generation, gender, race, or social class.
[src:hertz/adult] Social scientists regard these aspects as paramount in cultural definitions of adulthood.
[src:hertz/adult] Further evidence of adulthood as a social construction is illustrated by the changing criteria of adulthood over time.
[src:hertz/adult] Historically, adulthood in the U.S. has rested on completing one's education, moving away from the family of origin, and beginning one's career.
[src:hertz/adult] Other key historical criteria include entering a marriage and becoming a parent.
[src:hertz/adult] These criteria are social and subjective; they are organized by gender, race, ethnicity, and social class, among other key identity markers.
[src:hertz/adult] As a result, particular populations feel adult earlier in the life course than do others.
[src:hertz/adult] Contemporary experiences of and research on young adults today substitute more seemingly subjective criteria for adulthood which resonate more soundly with young adults' experiences of aging.
[src:hertz/adult] Jeffrey Arnett, a psychologist and professor at Clark University in Massachusetts, studied the development of adults and argues that there is a new and distinct period of development in between adolescence and adulthood.
[src:hertz/adult] This stage, which he calls "emerging adulthood", occurs between the ages of 18 and 25.
[src:hertz/adult] Arnett describes these individuals as able to take some responsibility for their lives, but still not completely feeling like an adult.
[src:hertz/adult] Arnett articulates five distinct features that are unique to this period of development: identity exploration, feeling in between, instability, self-focus, and having possibilities.
[src:hertz/adult] Arnett makes it clear that these 5 aspects of emerging adulthood are only relevant during the life stage of emerging adulthood.
[src:hertz/adult] The first feature, identity exploration, describes emerging adults making decisions for themselves about their career, education, and love life.
[src:hertz/adult] This is a time of life when a young person has yet to finalize these decisions but are pondering them, making them feel somewhere in between adolescent and adult.
[src:hertz/adult] This leads into a second feature of this phase of life—feeling in between.
[src:hertz/adult] Emerging adults feel that they are taking on responsibilities but do not feel like a 'full' adult quite yet.
[src:hertz/adult] Next, the instability feature notes that emerging adults often move around after their high school years whether that is to college, friends' houses, or living with a romantic partner, as well as moving back home with their parents/guardians for a time.
[src:hertz/adult] This moving around often ends once the individual's family and career have been set.
[src:hertz/adult] Tagging along with the instability feature is having self-focus.
[src:hertz/adult] Emerging adults, being away from their parental and societal routines, are now able to do what they want when they want and where they want before they are put back into a routine when they start a marriage, family, and career.
[src:hertz/adult] Arnett's last feature of emerging adulthood, an age of possibilities, characterizes this stage as one where "optimism reigns".
[src:hertz/adult] These individuals believe they have a good chance of turning out better than their parents did.
[src:hertz/adult] According to Jewish tradition, adulthood is reached at age 13 for Jewish boys and 12 for Jewish girls in accordance with the Bar or Bat Mitzvah; they are expected to demonstrate preparation for adulthood by learning the Torah and other Jewish practices.
[src:hertz/adult] The Christian Bible and Jewish scripture contain no age requirement for adulthood or marrying, which includes engaging in sexual activity.
[src:hertz/adult] The 1983 Code of Canon Law states, "A man before he has completed his sixteenth year of age, and likewise a woman before she has completed her fourteenth year of age, cannot enter a valid marriage".
[src:hertz/adult] According to *The Disappearance of Childhood* by Neil Postman, the Christian Church of the Middle Ages considered the age of accountability, when a person could be tried and even executed as an adult, to be age 7.
[src:hertz/adult] While certain religions have their guidelines on what it means to be an adult, generally speaking, there are trends that occur regarding religiosity as individuals transition from adolescence to adulthood.
[src:hertz/adult] The role of religion in one's life can impact development during adolescence.
[src:hertz/adult] The National Library of Medicine (NCBI) highlights some studies that show rates of religiosity declining as people move out of the house and live on their own.
[src:hertz/adult] Oftentimes when people live on their own, they change their life goals and religion tends to be less important as they discover who they are.
[src:hertz/adult] Other studies from the NCBI show that as adults get married and have children they settle down, and as they do, there tends to be an increase in religiosity.
[src:hertz/adult] Everyone's level of religiosity builds at a different pace, meaning that religion relative to adult development varies across cultures and time.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] The usual waveform of alternating current in most electric power circuits is a sine wave, whose positive half-period corresponds with positive direction of the current and vice versa (the full period is called a *cycle*).
[src:hertz/alternating-current] "Alternating current" most commonly refers to power distribution, but a wide range of other applications are technically alternating current although it is less common to describe them by that term.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] In many applications, like guitar amplifiers, different waveforms are used, such as triangular waves or square waves.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] Audio and radio signals carried on electrical wires are also examples of alternating current.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] These types of alternating current carry information such as sound (audio) or images (video) sometimes carried by modulation of an AC carrier signal.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] These currents typically alternate at higher frequencies than those used in power transmission.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] Electrical energy is distributed as alternating current because AC voltage may be increased or decreased with a transformer.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] This allows the power to be transmitted through power lines efficiently at high voltage, which reduces the energy lost as heat due to resistance of the wire, and transformed to a lower, safer voltage for use.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] Use of a higher voltage leads to significantly more efficient transmission of power.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] This means that when transmitting a fixed power on a given wire, if the current is halved (by doubling the voltage), the power loss due to the wire's resistance will be reduced by a factor of four.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] Consequently, power transmitted at a higher voltage requires less loss-producing current than for the same power at a lower voltage.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] Power is often transmitted at hundreds of kilovolts on pylons, and transformed down to tens of kilovolts to be transmitted on lower level lines, and finally transformed down to 100 V – 240 V for domestic use.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] High voltages have disadvantages, such as the increased insulation required, and generally increased difficulty in their safe handling.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] In a power plant, energy is generated at a convenient voltage for the design of a generator, and then stepped up to a high voltage for transmission.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] Near the loads, the transmission voltage is stepped down to the voltages used by equipment.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] Consumer voltages vary somewhat depending on the country and size of load, but generally motors and lighting are built to use up to a few hundred volts between phases.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] The voltage delivered to equipment such as lighting and motor loads is standardized, with an allowable range of voltage over which equipment is expected to operate.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] Standard power utilization voltages and percentage tolerance vary in the different mains power systems found in the world.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] High-voltage direct-current (HVDC) electric power transmission systems have become more viable as technology has provided efficient means of changing the voltage of DC power.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] Transmission with high voltage direct current was not feasible in the early days of electric power transmission, as there was then no economically viable way to step the voltage of DC down for end user applications such as lighting incandescent bulbs.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] Three-phase electrical generation is very common.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] The simplest way is to use three separate coils in the generator stator, physically offset by an angle of 120° (one-third of a complete 360° phase) to each other.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] Three current waveforms are produced that are equal in magnitude and 120° out of phase to each other.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] If coils are added opposite to these (60° spacing), they generate the same phases with reverse polarity and can be wired together.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] In practice, higher *pole orders* are commonly used.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] For example, a 12-pole machine would have 36 coils (10° spacing).
[src:hertz/alternating-current] The advantage is that lower rotational speeds can be used to generate the same frequency.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] For example, a 2-pole machine running at 3600 rpm and a 12-pole machine running at 600 rpm produce the same frequency; the lower speed is preferable for larger machines.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] If the load on a three-phase system is balanced equally among the phases, no current flows through the neutral point.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] Even in the worst-case unbalanced (linear) load, the neutral current will not exceed the highest of the phase currents.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] Non-linear loads (e.g. the switch-mode power supplies widely used) may require an oversized neutral bus and neutral conductor in the upstream distribution panel to handle harmonics.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] Harmonics can cause neutral conductor current levels to exceed that of one or all phase conductors.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] For three-phase at utilization voltages a four-wire system is often used.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] When stepping down three-phase, a transformer with a Delta (3-wire) primary and a Star (4-wire, center-earthed) secondary is often used so there is no need for a neutral on the supply side.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] For smaller customers (just how small varies by country and age of the installation) only a single phase and neutral, or two phases and neutral, are taken to the property.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] For larger installations, all three phases and neutral are taken to the main distribution panel.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] From the three-phase main panel, both single and three-phase circuits may lead off.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] Three-wire single-phase systems, with a single center-tapped transformer giving two live conductors, is a common distribution scheme for residential and small commercial buildings in North America.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] This arrangement is sometimes incorrectly referred to as *two phase*.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] A similar method is used for a different reason on construction sites in the UK.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] Small power tools and lighting are supposed to be supplied by a local center-tapped transformer with a voltage of 55 V between each power conductor and earth.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] This significantly reduces the risk of electric shock in the event that one of the live conductors becomes exposed through an equipment fault whilst still allowing a reasonable voltage of 110 V between the two conductors for running the tools.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] An additional wire, called the bond (or earth) wire, is often connected between non-current-carrying metal enclosures and earth ground.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] This conductor provides protection from electric shock due to accidental contact of circuit conductors with the metal chassis of portable appliances and tools.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] Bonding all non-current-carrying metal parts into one complete system ensures there is always a low electrical impedance path to ground sufficient to carry any fault current for as long as it takes for the system to clear the fault.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] This low impedance path allows the maximum amount of fault current, causing the overcurrent protection device (breakers, fuses) to trip or burn out as quickly as possible, bringing the electrical system to a safe state.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] All bond wires are bonded to ground at the main service panel, as is the neutral/identified conductor if present.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] The frequency of the electrical system varies by country and sometimes within a country; most electric power is generated at either 50 or 60 Hz.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] Some countries have a mixture of 50 Hz and 60 Hz supplies, notably electricity power transmission in Japan.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] A low frequency eases the design of electric motors, particularly for hoisting, crushing and rolling applications, and commutator-type traction motors for applications such as railways.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] However, low frequency also causes noticeable flicker in arc lamps and incandescent light bulbs.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] The use of lower frequencies also provided the advantage of lower transmission losses, which are proportional to frequency.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] The original Niagara Falls generators were built to produce 25 Hz power, as a compromise between low frequency for traction and heavy induction motors, while still allowing incandescent lighting to operate (although with noticeable flicker).
[src:hertz/alternating-current] Most of the 25 Hz residential and commercial customers for Niagara Falls power were converted to 60 Hz by the late 1950s, although some 25 Hz industrial customers still existed as of the start of the 21st century.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] 16.7 Hz power (formerly 16 2/3 Hz) is still used in some European rail systems, such as in Austria, Germany, Norway, Sweden and Switzerland.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] Off-shore, military, textile industry, marine, aircraft, and spacecraft applications sometimes use 400 Hz, for benefits of reduced weight of apparatus or higher motor speeds.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] Computer mainframe systems were often powered by 400 Hz or 415 Hz for benefits of ripple reduction while using smaller internal AC to DC conversion units.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] A direct current flows uniformly throughout the cross-section of a homogeneous electrically conducting wire.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] An alternating current of any frequency is forced away from the wire's center, toward its outer surface.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] This is because an alternating current (which is the result of the acceleration of electric charge) creates electromagnetic waves (a phenomenon known as electromagnetic radiation).
[src:hertz/alternating-current] The phenomenon of alternating current being pushed away from the center of the conductor is called skin effect, and a direct current does not exhibit this effect, since a direct current does not create electromagnetic waves.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] At very high frequencies, the current no longer flows *in* the wire, but effectively flows *on* the surface of the wire, within a thickness of a few skin depths.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] The skin depth is the thickness at which the current density is reduced by 63%.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] Even at relatively low frequencies used for power transmission (50 Hz – 60 Hz), non-uniform distribution of current still occurs in sufficiently thick conductors.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] For example, the skin depth of a copper conductor is approximately 8.57 mm at 60 Hz, so high-current conductors are usually hollow to reduce their mass and cost.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] This tendency of alternating current to flow predominantly in the periphery of conductors reduces the effective cross-section of the conductor.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] This increases the effective AC resistance of the conductor since resistance is inversely proportional to the cross-sectional area.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] A conductor's AC resistance is higher than its DC resistance, causing a higher energy loss due to Ohmic heating (also called I2R loss).
[src:hertz/alternating-current] For low to medium frequencies, conductors can be divided into stranded wires, each insulated from the others, with the relative positions of individual strands specially arranged within the conductor bundle.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] Wire constructed using this technique is called Litz wire.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] This measure helps to partially mitigate skin effect by forcing more equal current throughout the total cross section of the stranded conductors.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] As written above, an alternating current is made of electric charge under periodic acceleration, which causes radiation of electromagnetic waves.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] Depending on the frequency, different techniques are used to minimize the loss due to radiation.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] At frequencies up to about 1 GHz, pairs of wires are twisted together in a cable, forming a twisted pair.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] This reduces losses from electromagnetic radiation and inductive coupling.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] A twisted pair must be used with a balanced signaling system so that the two wires carry equal but opposite currents.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] Each wire in a twisted pair radiates a signal, but it is effectively canceled by radiation from the other wire, resulting in almost no radiation loss.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] Coaxial cables are commonly used at audio frequencies and above for convenience.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] A coaxial cable has a conductive wire inside a conductive tube, separated by a dielectric layer.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] The current flowing on the surface of the inner conductor is equal and opposite to the current flowing on the inner surface of the outer tube.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] The electromagnetic field is thus completely contained within the tube, and (ideally) no energy is lost to radiation or coupling outside the tube.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] Coaxial cables have acceptably small losses for frequencies up to about 5 GHz.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] For microwave frequencies greater than 5 GHz, the losses (due mainly to the dielectric separating the inner and outer tubes being a non-ideal insulator) become too large, making waveguides a more efficient medium for transmitting energy.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] Coaxial cables often use a perforated dielectric layer to separate the inner and outer conductors in order to minimize the power dissipated by the dielectric.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] Waveguides are similar to coaxial cables, as both consist of tubes, with the biggest difference being that waveguides have no inner conductor.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] Waveguides can have any arbitrary cross section, but rectangular cross sections are the most common.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] Because waveguides do not have an inner conductor to carry a return current, waveguides cannot deliver energy by means of an electric current, but rather by means of a *guided* electromagnetic field.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] Although surface currents do flow on the inner walls of the waveguides, those surface currents do not carry power.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] Power is carried by the guided electromagnetic fields.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] The surface currents are set up by the guided electromagnetic fields and have the effect of keeping the fields inside the waveguide and preventing leakage of the fields to the space outside the waveguide.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] Waveguides have dimensions comparable to the wavelength of the alternating current to be transmitted, so they are feasible only at microwave frequencies.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] In addition to this mechanical feasibility, electrical resistance of the non-ideal metals forming the walls of the waveguide causes dissipation of power (surface currents flowing on lossy conductors dissipate power).
[src:hertz/alternating-current] At higher frequencies, the power lost to this dissipation becomes unacceptably large.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] At frequencies greater than 200 GHz, waveguide dimensions become impractically small, and the ohmic losses in the waveguide walls become large.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] Instead, fiber optics, which are a form of dielectric waveguides, can be used.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] For such frequencies, the concepts of voltages and currents are no longer used.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] Alternating currents are accompanied (or caused) by alternating voltages.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] The peak-to-peak value of an AC voltage is defined as the difference between its positive peak and its negative peak.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] Since the maximum value of $\sin(x)$ is +1 and the minimum value is −1, an AC voltage swings between $+V_{\text{peak}}$ and $-V_{\text{peak}}$ .
[src:hertz/alternating-current] Below an AC waveform (with no DC component) is assumed.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] The RMS voltage is the square root of the mean over one cycle of the square of the instantaneous voltage.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] Rather than using instantaneous power, $p(t)$ , it is more practical to use a time-averaged power (where the averaging is performed over any integer number of cycles).
[src:hertz/alternating-current] For this reason, AC power's waveform becomes Full-wave rectified sine, and its fundamental frequency is double that of the voltage's.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] To illustrate these concepts, consider a 230 V AC mains supply used in many countries around the world.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] It is so called because its root mean square value is 230 V.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] This means that the time-averaged power delivered $P_{\text{average}}$ is equivalent to the power delivered by a DC voltage of 230 V.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] For 230 V AC, the peak voltage $V_{\text{peak}}$ is therefore $230{\text{ V}}\times {\sqrt {2}}$ , which is about 325 V, and the peak power $P_{\text{peak}}$ is $230\times R\times W\times 2$ , that is 460 RW.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] During the course of one cycle (two cycle as the power) the voltage rises from zero to 325 V, the power from zero to 460 RW, and both falls through zero.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] Next, the voltage descends to reverse direction, −325 V, but the power ascends again to 460 RW, and both returns to zero.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] Alternating current is used to transmit information, as in the cases of telephone and cable television.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] Information signals are carried over a wide range of AC frequencies.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] POTS telephone signals have a frequency of about 3 kHz, close to the baseband audio frequency.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] Cable television and other cable-transmitted information currents may alternate at frequencies of tens to thousands of megahertz.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] These frequencies are similar to the electromagnetic wave frequencies often used to transmit the same types of information over the air.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] The first alternator to produce alternating current was an electric generator based on Michael Faraday's principles constructed by the French instrument maker Hippolyte Pixii in 1832.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] Pixii later added a commutator to his device to produce the (then) more commonly used direct current.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] The earliest recorded practical application of alternating current is by Guillaume Duchenne, inventor and developer of electrotherapy.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] In 1855, he announced that AC was superior to direct current for electrotherapeutic triggering of muscle contractions.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] Alternating current technology was developed further by the Hungarian Ganz Works company in the 1870s, and, in the 1880s, by Sebastian Ziani de Ferranti, Lucien Gaulard, and Galileo Ferraris.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] In 1876, Russian engineer Pavel Yablochkov invented a lighting system where sets of induction coils were installed along a high-voltage AC line.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] Instead of changing voltage, the primary windings transferred power to the secondary windings which were connected to one or several electric candles (arc lamps) of his own design, used to keep the failure of one lamp from disabling the entire circuit.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] In 1878, the Ganz factory, Budapest, Hungary, began manufacturing equipment for electric lighting and, by 1883, had installed over fifty systems in Austria-Hungary.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] Their AC systems used arc and incandescent lamps, generators, and other equipment.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] The development of the alternating current transformer to change voltage from low to high level and back, allowed generation and consumption at low voltages and transmission, over great distances, at high voltage, with savings in the cost of conductors and energy losses.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] A bipolar open-core power transformer developed by Lucien Gaulard and John Dixon Gibbs was demonstrated in London in 1881, and attracted the interest of Westinghouse.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] They exhibited an AC system powering arc and incandescent lights was installed along five railway stations for the Metropolitan Railway in London and a single-phase multiple-user AC distribution system Turin in 1884.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] These early induction coils with open magnetic circuits were inefficient at transferring power to loads.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] Until about 1880, the paradigm for AC power transmission from a high voltage supply to a low voltage load was a series circuit.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] Open-core transformers with a ratio near 1:1 were connected with their primaries in series to allow use of a high voltage for transmission while presenting a low voltage to the lamps.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] The inherent flaw in this method was that turning off a single lamp (or other electronic device) affected the voltage supplied to all others on the same circuit.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] Many adjustable transformer designs were introduced to compensate for this problematic characteristic of the series circuit, including those employing methods of adjusting the core or bypassing the magnetic flux around part of a coil.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] The direct current systems did not have these drawbacks, giving it significant advantages over early AC systems.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] In 1890, he designed their power station at Deptford and converted the Grosvenor Gallery station across the Thames into an electrical substation, showing the way to integrate older plants into a universal AC supply system.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] In the autumn of 1884, Károly Zipernowsky, Ottó Bláthy and Miksa Déri (ZBD), three engineers associated with the Ganz Works of Budapest, determined that open-core devices were impractical, as they were incapable of reliably regulating voltage.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] In both designs, the magnetic flux linking the primary and secondary windings traveled almost entirely within the confines of the iron core, with no intentional path through air (see toroidal cores).
[src:hertz/alternating-current] The new transformers were 3.4 times more efficient than the open-core bipolar devices of Gaulard and Gibbs.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] The Ganz factory in 1884 shipped the world's first five high-efficiency AC transformers.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] This first unit had been manufactured to the following specifications: 1,400 W, 40 Hz, 120:72 V, 11.6:19.4 A, ratio 1.67:1, one-phase, shell form.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] When employed in parallel connected electric distribution systems, closed-core transformers finally made it technically and economically feasible to provide electric power for lighting in homes, businesses and public spaces.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] The other essential milestone was the introduction of 'voltage source, voltage intensive' (VSVI) systems' by the invention of constant voltage generators in 1885.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] In early 1885, the three engineers also eliminated the problem of eddy current losses with the invention of the lamination of electromagnetic cores.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] Ottó Bláthy also invented the first AC electricity meter.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] In May 1885, at the Hungarian National Exhibition in Budapest, Deri, Blathy, and Zipernowski held a large-scale demonstration of what is widely regarded as the prototype of modern AC lighting systems.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] Their system used 75 transformers in parallel connection, supplying 1,067 incandescent Edison lamps from an AC generator that provided 1,350 V.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] The AC power system was developed and adopted rapidly after 1886.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] With this setup, the Westinghouse company successfully powered thirty 100-volt incandescent bulbs in twenty shops along the main street of Great Barrington.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] By the fall of that year Ganz engineers installed a ZBD transformer power system with AC generators in Rome.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] Based on Stanley's success, the new Westinghouse Electric went on to develop alternating current (AC) electric infrastructure throughout the United States.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] The spread of Westinghouse and other AC systems triggered a push back in late 1887 by Thomas Edison (a proponent of direct current), who attempted to discredit alternating current as too dangerous in a public campaign called the "war of the currents".
[src:hertz/alternating-current] In 1888, alternating current systems gained further viability with the introduction of a functional AC motor, something these systems had lacked up till then.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] The design, an induction motor, was independently invented by Galileo Ferraris and Nikola Tesla (with Tesla's design being licensed by Westinghouse in the US).
[src:hertz/alternating-current] This design was independently further developed into the modern practical three-phase form by Mikhail Dolivo-Dobrovolsky and Charles Eugene Lancelot Brown in Germany on one side, and Jonas Wenström in Sweden on the other, though Brown favored the two-phase system.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] The Ames Hydroelectric Generating Plant, constructed in 1890, was among the first hydroelectric alternating current power plants.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] A long-distance transmission of single-phase electricity from a hydroelectric generating plant in Oregon at Willamette Falls sent power fourteen miles downriver to downtown Portland for street lighting in 1890.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] In 1891, another transmission system was installed in Telluride Colorado.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] The first three-phase system was established in 1891 in Frankfurt, Germany.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] The Tivoli–Rome transmission was completed in 1892.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] The San Antonio Canyon Generator was the third commercial single-phase hydroelectric AC power plant in the United States to provide long-distance electricity.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] It was completed on December 31, 1892, by Almarian William Decker to provide power to the city of Pomona, California, which was 14 miles away.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] Meanwhile, the possibility of transferring electrical power from a waterfall at a distance was explored at the Grängesberg mine in Sweden.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] A 45 m fall at Hällsjön, Smedjebackens kommun, where a small iron work had been located, was selected.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] In 1893, a three-phase 9.5 kv system was used to transfer 400 horsepower a distance of 15 km, becoming the first commercial application.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] In 1893, Westinghouse built an alternating current system for the Chicago World Exposition.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] In 1893, Decker designed the first American commercial three-phase power plant using alternating current—the hydroelectric Mill Creek No.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] 1 Hydroelectric Plant near Redlands, California.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] Decker's design incorporated 10 kV three-phase transmission and established the standards for the complete system of generation, transmission and motors used in USA today.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] The original Niagara Falls Adams Power Plant with three two-phase generators was put into operation in August 1895, but was connected to the remote transmission system only in 1896.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] The Jaruga Hydroelectric Power Plant in Croatia was set in operation two days later, on 28 August 1895.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] Its generator (42 Hz, 240 kW) was made and installed by the Hungarian company Ganz, while the transmission line from the power plant to the City of Šibenik was 11.5 kilometers (7.1 mi) long, and the municipal distribution grid 3000 V/110 V included six transforming stations.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] Alternating current circuit theory developed rapidly in the latter part of the 19th and early 20th century.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] Notable contributors to the theoretical basis of alternating current calculations include Charles Steinmetz, Oliver Heaviside, and many others.
[src:hertz/alternating-current] Calculations in unbalanced three-phase systems were simplified by the symmetrical components methods discussed by Charles LeGeyt Fortescue in 1918.
[src:hertz/ampere] The **ampere** (/ˈæmpɛər/ ⓘ *AM-pair*, US: /ˈæmpɪər/ ⓘ *AM-peer*; symbol: **A**), often shortened to **amp**, is the unit of electric current in the International System of Units (SI).
[src:hertz/ampere] One ampere is equal to 1 coulomb (C) moving past a point per second.
[src:hertz/ampere] It is named after French mathematician and physicist André-Marie Ampère (1775–1836), considered the father of electromagnetism along with Danish physicist Hans Christian Ørsted.
[src:hertz/ampere] Prior to the redefinition, the ampere was defined as the current passing through two parallel wires 1 metre apart that produces a magnetic force of 2×10−7 newtons per metre.
[src:hertz/ampere] The earlier CGS system has two units of current, one structured similarly to the SI's and the other using Coulomb's law as a fundamental relationship, with the CGS unit of charge defined by measuring the force between two charged metal plates.
[src:hertz/ampere] The CGS unit of current is then defined as one unit of charge per second.
[src:hertz/ampere] The ampere is named for French physicist and mathematician André-Marie Ampère (1775–1836), who studied electromagnetism and laid the foundation of electrodynamics.
[src:hertz/ampere] In recognition of Ampère's contributions to the creation of modern electrical science, an international convention, signed at the 1881 International Exposition of Electricity, established the ampere as a standard unit of electrical measurement for electric current.
[src:hertz/ampere] The ampere was originally defined as one tenth of the unit of electric current in the centimetre–gram–second system of units.
[src:hertz/ampere] That unit, now known as the abampere, was defined as the amount of current that generates a force of two dynes per centimetre of length between two wires one centimetre apart.
[src:hertz/ampere] The size of the unit was chosen so that the units derived from it in the MKSA system would be conveniently sized.
[src:hertz/ampere] The "international ampere" was an early realisation of the ampere, defined as the current that would deposit 0.001118 grams of silver per second from a silver nitrate solution.
[src:hertz/ampere] Later, more accurate measurements revealed that this current is 0.99985 A.
[src:hertz/ampere] Since power is defined as the product of current and voltage, the ampere can alternatively be expressed in terms of the other units using the relationship *I* = *P*/*V*, and thus 1 A = 1 W/V.
[src:hertz/ampere] Current can be measured by a multimeter, a device that can measure electrical voltage, current, and resistance.
[src:hertz/ampere] Ampère's force law states that there is an attractive or repulsive force between two parallel wires carrying an electric current.
[src:hertz/ampere] This force was used in the formal definition of the ampere, giving the vacuum magnetic permeability (magnetic constant, *μ*0) a value of exactly 4π × 10−7 henries per metre (H/m, equivalent to N/A2).
[src:hertz/ampere] The SI unit of charge, the coulomb, was then defined as "the quantity of electricity carried in 1 second by a current of 1 ampere".
[src:hertz/ampere] In general, charge Q was determined by steady current I flowing for a time t as *Q* = *It*.
[src:hertz/ampere] Techniques to establish the realisation of an ampere had a relative uncertainty of approximately a few parts in 107, and involved realisations of the watt, the ohm and the volt.
[src:hertz/ampere] The SI unit of charge, the coulomb, "is the quantity of electricity carried in 1 second by a current of 1 ampere".
[src:hertz/ampere] The relation of the ampere (A = C/s) to the coulomb (C) is the same as that of the watt (W = J/s) to the joule (J).
[src:hertz/ampere] These SI derived units can either be given special names e.g. watt, volt, lux, etc. or defined in terms of others, e.g. metre per second.
[src:hertz/ampere] There are also some SI units that are frequently used in the context of electrical engineering and electrical appliances, but are defined independently of the ampere, notably the hertz, joule, watt, candela, lumen, and lux.
[src:hertz/ampere] Like other SI units, the ampere can be modified by adding a prefix that multiplies it by a power of 10.
[src:hertz/angular-frequency] Angular frequency (or angular speed) is the magnitude of the pseudovector quantity *angular velocity*.
[src:hertz/angular-frequency] Angular frequency can be obtained by multiplying *rotational frequency*, *ν* (or ordinary *frequency*, *f*) by a full turn (2π radians): *ω* = 2π rad⋅*ν*.
[src:hertz/angular-frequency] It can also be formulated as *ω* = d*θ*/d*t*, the instantaneous rate of change of the angular displacement, *θ*, with respect to time, *t*.
[src:hertz/angular-frequency] In SI units, angular frequency is normally presented in the unit radian per second.
[src:hertz/angular-frequency] The unit hertz (Hz) is dimensionally equivalent, but by convention it is only used for frequency *f*, never for angular frequency *ω*.
[src:hertz/angular-frequency] This convention is used to help avoid the confusion that arises when dealing with quantities such as frequency and angular quantities because the units of measure (such as cycle or radian) are considered to be one and hence may be omitted when expressing quantities in terms of SI units.
[src:hertz/angular-frequency] In digital signal processing, the frequency may be normalized by the sampling rate, yielding the normalized frequency.
[src:hertz/angular-frequency] In a rotating or orbiting object, there is a relation between distance from the axis, r , tangential speed, v , and the angular frequency of the rotation.
[src:hertz/angular-frequency] During one period, T , a body in circular motion travels a distance $vT$ .
[src:hertz/angular-frequency] This distance is also equal to the circumference of the path traced out by the body, $2\pi r$ .
[src:hertz/angular-frequency] An object attached to a spring can oscillate.
[src:hertz/angular-frequency] As the object oscillates, its acceleration can be calculated by $a=-\omega ^{2}x,$ where *x* is displacement from an equilibrium position.
[src:hertz/angular-frequency] Adding series resistance (for example, due to the resistance of the wire in a coil) does not change the resonant frequency of the series LC circuit.
[src:hertz/angular-frequency] For a parallel tuned circuit, the above equation is often a useful approximation, but the resonant frequency does depend on the losses of parallel elements.
[src:hertz/angular-frequency] Although angular frequency is often loosely referred to as frequency, it differs from frequency by a factor of 2π, which potentially leads confusion when the distinction is not made clear.
[src:hertz/angular-velocity] The direction ${\hat {\boldsymbol {\omega }}}={\boldsymbol {\omega }}/\|{\boldsymbol {\omega }}\|$ is normal to the instantaneous plane of rotation.
[src:hertz/angular-velocity] The sense of angular velocity is conventionally specified by the right-hand rule, implying clockwise rotations (as viewed on the plane of rotation); negation (multiplication by −1) leaves the magnitude unchanged but flips the axis in the opposite direction.
[src:hertz/angular-velocity] The magnitude of this vector, $\omega =\|{\boldsymbol {\omega }}\|$ , represents the *angular speed*, the angular rate at which the object rotates (spins or revolves).
[src:hertz/angular-velocity] The angular velocity as given above for point particles, is called orbital angular velocity.
[src:hertz/angular-velocity] A rigid body rotating about a fixed axis has each point of the body having the same orbital angular velocity.
[src:hertz/angular-velocity] Hence such a rigid body can be given an angular velocity (called spin angular velocity) equal to the orbital angular velocity of each point in the body.
[src:hertz/angular-velocity] The angular velocity, as given above for rotation in a fixed circle at constant speed, can be generalized to more general motion in three dimensions.
[src:hertz/angular-velocity] Angular velocity has dimension of per unit time.
[src:hertz/angular-velocity] The SI unit of angular velocity is radians per second,.
[src:hertz/angular-velocity] The radian is a dimensionless quantity, thus the SI units of angular velocity are dimensionally equivalent to reciprocal seconds, s−1, although rad/s is preferable to avoid confusion with **rotational velocity** in units of hertz (also equivalent to s−1).
[src:hertz/angular-velocity] If angle is measured in radians, the linear velocity is the radius times the angular velocity, ⁠ $v=r\omega$ ⁠.
[src:hertz/angular-velocity] With orbital radius 42000 km from the Earth's center, the satellite's tangential speed through space is thus *v* = 42000 km × 0.26/h ≈ 11000 km/h.
[src:hertz/angular-velocity] The angular velocity is positive since the satellite travels prograde with the Earth's rotation (the same direction as the rotation of Earth).
[src:hertz/angular-velocity] In the simplest case of circular motion at radius ⁠ r ⁠, with position given by the angular displacement $\phi (t)$ from the x-axis, the orbital angular velocity is the rate of change of angle with respect to time: ⁠ $\textstyle \omega ={\frac {d\phi }{dt}}$ ⁠.
[src:hertz/angular-velocity] If $\phi$ is measured in radians, the arc-length from the positive x-axis around the circle to the particle is ⁠ $\ell =r\phi$ ⁠, and the linear velocity is ⁠ $\textstyle v(t)={\frac {d\ell }{dt}}=r\omega (t)$ ⁠, so that ⁠ $\textstyle \omega ={\frac {v}{r}}$ ⁠.
[src:hertz/angular-velocity] In the general case of a particle moving in the plane, the orbital angular velocity is the rate at which the position vector relative to a chosen origin "sweeps out" angle.
[src:hertz/angular-velocity] The diagram shows the position vector $\mathbf {r}$ from the origin O to a particle ⁠ P ⁠, with its polar coordinates ⁠ $(r,\phi )$ ⁠.
[src:hertz/angular-velocity] When there is no radial component, the particle moves around the origin in a circle; but when there is no cross-radial component, it moves in a straight line from the origin.
[src:hertz/angular-velocity] Since radial motion leaves the angle unchanged, only the cross-radial component of linear velocity contributes to angular velocity.
[src:hertz/angular-velocity] Here the cross-radial speed $v_{\perp }$ is the signed magnitude of ⁠ $\mathbf {v} _{\perp }$ ⁠, positive for counter-clockwise motion, negative for clockwise.
[src:hertz/angular-velocity] These formulas may be derived doing ⁠ $\mathbf {r} =(r\cos(\varphi ),r\sin(\varphi ))$ ⁠, being r a function of the distance to the origin with respect to time, and $\varphi$ a function of the angle between the vector and the x-axis.
[src:hertz/angular-velocity] In two dimensions, angular velocity is a number with plus or minus sign indicating orientation, but not pointing in a direction.
[src:hertz/angular-velocity] The sign is conventionally taken to be positive if the radius vector turns counter-clockwise, and negative if clockwise.
[src:hertz/angular-velocity] Angular velocity then may be termed a pseudoscalar, a numerical quantity which changes sign under a parity inversion, such as inverting one axis or switching the two axes.
[src:hertz/angular-velocity] In three-dimensional space, we again have the position vector **r** of a moving particle.
[src:hertz/angular-velocity] Here, orbital angular velocity is a pseudovector whose magnitude is the rate at which **r** sweeps out angle (in radians per unit of time), and whose direction is perpendicular to the instantaneous plane in which **r** sweeps out angle (i.e. the plane spanned by **r** and **v**).
[src:hertz/angular-velocity] However, as there are *two* directions perpendicular to any plane, an additional condition is necessary to uniquely specify the direction of the angular velocity; conventionally, the right-hand rule is used.
[src:hertz/angular-velocity] Let the pseudovector $\mathbf {u}$ be the unit vector perpendicular to the plane spanned by **r** and **v**, so that the right-hand rule is satisfied (i.e. the instantaneous direction of angular displacement is counter-clockwise looking from the top of ⁠ $\mathbf {u}$ ⁠).
[src:hertz/angular-velocity] where ⁠ $\theta$ ⁠ is the angle between ⁠ $\mathbf {r}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\mathbf {v}$ ⁠.
[src:hertz/angular-velocity] Given a rotating frame of three linearly independent unit coordinate vectors, at each instant in time, there always exists a common axis (called the axis of rotation) around which all three vectors rotate with the same angular speed and in the same angular direction (clockwise or counterclockwise).
[src:hertz/angular-velocity] In such a frame, each vector may be considered as a moving particle with constant scalar radius.
[src:hertz/angular-velocity] A collection of such particles is called a rigid body.
[src:hertz/angular-velocity] In larger than 3 spatial dimensions, the interpretation of spin angular velocity as a pseudovector is not valid; however, it may be characterized by a more general type of object known as an antisymmetric rank-2 tensor.
[src:hertz/angular-velocity] The addition of angular velocity vectors for frames is also defined by the usual vector addition (composition of linear movements), and can be useful to decompose the rotation as in a gimbal.
[src:hertz/angular-velocity] All components of the vector can be calculated as derivatives of the parameters defining the moving frames (Euler angles or rotation matrices).
[src:hertz/angular-velocity] Consider a rigid body rotating about a fixed point O.
[src:hertz/angular-velocity] Construct a reference frame in the body consisting of an orthonormal set of vectors $\mathbf {e} _{1},\mathbf {e} _{2},\mathbf {e} _{3}$ fixed to the body and with their common origin at O.
[src:hertz/angular-velocity] where ${\dot {\mathbf {e} }}_{i}={\frac {d\mathbf {e} _{i}}{dt}}$ is the time rate of change of the frame vector ⁠ $\mathbf {e} _{i},i=1,2,3$ ⁠, due to the rotation.
[src:hertz/angular-velocity] as that formula defines angular velocity for a *single point* about O, while the formula in this section applies to a frame or rigid body.
[src:hertz/angular-velocity] In the case of a rigid body a *single* ${\boldsymbol {\omega }}$ has to account for the motion of *all* particles in the body.
[src:hertz/angular-velocity] Euler proved that the projections of the angular velocity pseudovector on each of these three axes is the derivative of its associated angle (which is equivalent to decomposing the instantaneous rotation into three instantaneous Euler rotations).
[src:hertz/angular-velocity] This basis is not orthonormal and it is difficult to use, but now the velocity vector can be changed to the fixed frame or to the moving frame with just a change of bases.
[src:hertz/angular-velocity] where ${\hat {\mathbf {i} }},{\hat {\mathbf {j} }},{\hat {\mathbf {k} }}$ are unit vectors for the frame fixed in the moving body.
[src:hertz/angular-velocity] This example has been made using the Z-X-Z convention for Euler angles.
[src:hertz/angular-velocity] The scalar elements above correspond to the angular velocity vector components ${\boldsymbol {\omega }}=(\omega _{x},\omega _{y},\omega _{z})$ .
[src:hertz/angular-velocity] This is an *infinitesimal rotation matrix*.
[src:hertz/angular-velocity] where ${\boldsymbol {r}}$ is a position vector.
[src:hertz/angular-velocity] When multiplied by a time difference, it results in the *angular displacement tensor*.
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] The interval of time between events is called the **period**.
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] For example, if a heart beats at a frequency of 120 times per minute (2 hertz), its period is one half of a second.
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] Special definitions of frequency are used in certain contexts, such as the angular frequency in rotational or cyclical properties, when the rate of angular progress is measured.
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] Spatial frequency is defined for properties that vary or occur repeatedly in geometry or space.
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] The unit of measurement of frequency in the International System of Units (SI) is the hertz, having the symbol Hz.
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] For cyclical phenomena such as oscillations, waves, or for examples of simple harmonic motion, the term *frequency* is defined as the number of cycles or repetitions per unit of time.
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] The conventional symbol for frequency is *f* or *ν* (the Greek letter nu) is also used.
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] The *period* *T* is the time taken to complete one cycle of an oscillation or rotation.
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] The term *temporal frequency* is used to emphasise that the frequency is characterised by the number of occurrences of a repeating event per unit time.
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] The SI unit of frequency is the hertz (Hz), named after the German physicist Heinrich Hertz by the International Electrotechnical Commission in 1930.
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] It was adopted by the CGPM (Conférence générale des poids et mesures) in 1960, officially replacing the previous name, *cycle per second* (cps).
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] The SI unit for the period, as for all measurements of time, is the second.
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] A traditional unit of frequency used with rotating mechanical devices, where it is termed *rotational frequency*, is revolution per minute, abbreviated r/min or rpm.
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] As a matter of convenience, longer and slower waves, such as ocean surface waves, are more typically described by wave period rather than frequency.
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] Short and fast waves, like audio and radio, are usually described by their frequency.
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] For periodic waves in nondispersive media (that is, media in which the wave speed is independent of frequency), frequency has an inverse relationship to the wavelength, *λ* (lambda).
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] When monochromatic waves travel from one medium to another, their frequency remains the same—only their wavelength and speed change.
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] Calculating the frequency of a repeating event is accomplished by counting the number of times that event occurs within a specific time period, then dividing the count by the period.
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] If the number of counts is not very large, it is more accurate to measure the time interval for a predetermined number of occurrences, rather than the number of occurrences within a specified time.
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] The latter method introduces a random error into the count of between zero and one count, so on average half a count.
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] This error decreases with frequency, so it is generally a problem at low frequencies where the number of counts *N* is small.
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] A resonant-reed frequency meter, an obsolete device used from about 1900 to the 1940s for measuring the frequency of alternating current.
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] at that frequency will vibrate with large amplitude, visible next to the scale.
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] An old method of measuring the frequency of rotating or vibrating objects is to use a stroboscope.
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] This is an intense repetitively flashing light (strobe light) whose frequency can be adjusted with a calibrated timing circuit.
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] The strobe light is pointed at the rotating object and the frequency adjusted up and down.
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] When the frequency of the strobe equals the frequency of the rotating or vibrating object, the object completes one cycle of oscillation and returns to its original position between the flashes of light, so when illuminated by the strobe the object appears stationary.
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] Then the frequency can be read from the calibrated readout on the stroboscope.
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] A downside of this method is that an object rotating at an integer multiple of the strobing frequency will also appear stationary.
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] Higher frequencies are usually measured with a frequency counter.
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] This is an electronic instrument which measures the frequency of an applied repetitive electronic signal and displays the result in hertz on a digital display.
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] It uses digital logic to count the number of cycles during a time interval established by a precision quartz time base.
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] Cyclic processes that are not electrical, such as the rotation rate of a shaft, mechanical vibrations, or sound waves, can be converted to a repetitive electronic signal by transducers and the signal applied to a frequency counter.
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] As of 2018, frequency counters can cover the range up to about 100 GHz.
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] This represents the limit of direct counting methods; frequencies above this must be measured by indirect methods.
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] Above the range of frequency counters, frequencies of electromagnetic signals are often measured indirectly utilizing heterodyning (frequency conversion).
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] A reference signal of a known frequency near the unknown frequency is mixed with the unknown frequency in a nonlinear mixing device such as a diode.
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] This creates a heterodyne or "beat" signal at the difference between the two frequencies.
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] If the two signals are close together in frequency the heterodyne is low enough to be measured by a frequency counter.
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] This process only measures the difference between the unknown frequency and the reference frequency.
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] To convert higher frequencies, several stages of heterodyning can be used.
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] Current research is extending this method to infrared and light frequencies (optical heterodyne detection).
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] Visible light is an electromagnetic wave, consisting of oscillating electric and magnetic fields traveling through space.
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] The frequency of the wave determines its color: 400 THz (4×1014 Hz) is red light, 800 THz (8×1014 Hz) is violet light, and between these (in the range 400–800 THz) are all the other colors of the visible spectrum.
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] An electromagnetic wave with a frequency less than 4×1014 Hz will be invisible to the human eye; such waves are called infrared (IR) radiation.
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] At even lower frequency, the wave is called a microwave, and at still lower frequencies it is called a radio wave.
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] Likewise, an electromagnetic wave with a frequency higher than 8×1014 Hz will also be invisible to the human eye; such waves are called ultraviolet (UV) radiation.
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] Even higher-frequency waves are called X-rays, and higher still are gamma rays.
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] All of these waves, from the lowest-frequency radio waves to the highest-frequency gamma rays, are fundamentally the same, and they are all called electromagnetic radiation.
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] They all travel through vacuum at the same speed (the speed of light), giving them wavelengths inversely proportional to their frequencies.
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] where *c* is the speed of light (*c* in vacuum or less in other media), *f* is the frequency and *λ* is the wavelength.
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] In dispersive media, such as glass, the speed depends somewhat on frequency, so the wavelength is not quite inversely proportional to frequency.
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] Sound propagates as mechanical vibration waves of pressure and displacement, in air or other substances.
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] In general, frequency components of a sound determine its "color", its timbre.
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] When speaking about the frequency (in singular) of a sound, it means the property that most determines its pitch.
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] The frequencies an ear can hear are limited to a specific range of frequencies.
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] The audible frequency range for humans is typically given as being between about 20 Hz and 20,000 Hz (20 kHz), though the high frequency limit usually reduces with age.
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] Other species have different hearing ranges.
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] For example, some dog breeds can perceive vibrations up to 60,000 Hz.
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] In many media, such as air, the speed of sound is approximately independent of frequency, so the wavelength of the sound waves (distance between repetitions) is approximately inversely proportional to frequency.
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] The frequency of the 'hum' in an audio recording can show in which of these general regions the recording was made.
[src:hertz/aperiodic-frequency] involving the number of entities counted or the number of events happened (*N*) during a given time duration (Δ*t*); it is a physical quantity of type temporal rate.
[src:hertz/hertz] The **hertz** (symbol: **Hz**) is the unit of frequency in the International System of Units (SI), often described as being equivalent to one event (or cycle) per second.
[src:hertz/hertz] The hertz is an SI derived unit whose formal expression in terms of SI base units is 1/s or s−1, meaning that one hertz is one per second or the reciprocal of one second.
[src:hertz/hertz] It is used only in the case of periodic events.
[src:hertz/hertz] It is named after Heinrich Rudolf Hertz (1857–1894), the first person to provide conclusive proof of the existence of electromagnetic waves.
[src:hertz/hertz] For high frequencies, the unit is commonly expressed in multiples: kilohertz (kHz), megahertz (MHz), gigahertz (GHz), terahertz (THz).
[src:hertz/hertz] Some of the unit's most common uses are in the description of periodic waveforms and musical tones, particularly those used in radio- and audio-related applications.
[src:hertz/hertz] It is also used to describe the clock speeds at which computers and other electronics are driven.
[src:hertz/hertz] The units are sometimes also used as a representation of the energy of a photon, via the Planck relation *E* = *hν*, where *E* is the photon's energy, *ν* is its frequency, and *h* is the Planck constant.
[src:hertz/hertz] The hertz is defined as one per second for periodic events.
[src:hertz/hertz] Expressed in base SI units, the unit is the reciprocal second (1/s).
[src:hertz/hertz] In English, "hertz" is also used as the plural form.
[src:hertz/hertz] As an SI unit, Hz can be prefixed; commonly used multiples are kHz (kilohertz, 103 Hz), MHz (megahertz, 106 Hz), GHz (gigahertz, 109 Hz) and THz (terahertz, 1012 Hz).
[src:hertz/hertz] One hertz (i.e. one per second) simply means "one periodic event occurs per second" (where the event being counted may be a complete cycle); 100 Hz means "one hundred periodic events occur per second", and so on.
[src:hertz/hertz] The unit may be applied to any periodic event—for example, a clock might be said to tick at 1 Hz, or a human heart might be said to beat at 1.2 Hz.
[src:hertz/hertz] The occurrence rate of aperiodic or stochastic events is expressed in *reciprocal second* or *inverse second* (1/s or s−1) in general or, in the specific case of radioactivity, in becquerels.
[src:hertz/hertz] Whereas 1 Hz (one per second) specifically refers to one cycle (or periodic event) per second, 1 Bq (also one per second) specifically refers to one radionuclide event per second on average.
[src:hertz/hertz] Even though frequency, angular velocity, angular frequency and radioactivity all have the dimension T−1, of these only frequency is expressed using the unit hertz.
[src:hertz/hertz] Thus a disc rotating at 60 revolutions per minute (rpm) is said to have an angular velocity of 2π rad/s and a frequency of rotation of 1 Hz.
[src:hertz/hertz] The hertz is named after Heinrich Hertz.
[src:hertz/hertz] As with every SI unit named after a person, its symbol starts with an upper case letter (Hz), but when written in full, it follows the rules for capitalisation of a common noun; i.e., *hertz* becomes capitalised at the beginning of a sentence and in titles but is otherwise in lower case.
[src:hertz/hertz] The hertz is named after the German physicist Heinrich Hertz (1857–1894), who made important scientific contributions to the study of electromagnetism.
[src:hertz/hertz] The name was established by the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) in 1935.
[src:hertz/hertz] In some circumstances, "megacycles" was used a contraction of "megacycles per second".
[src:hertz/hertz] Replacement of "cycles per second" by "hertz" in the popular press began in the late 1960s.
[src:hertz/hertz] Sound is a traveling longitudinal wave, which is an oscillation of pressure.
[src:hertz/hertz] Humans perceive the frequency of a sound as its pitch.
[src:hertz/hertz] Each musical note corresponds to a particular frequency.
[src:hertz/hertz] An infant's ear is able to perceive frequencies ranging from 20 Hz to 20000 Hz; the average adult human can hear sounds between 20 Hz and 16000 Hz.
[src:hertz/hertz] The range of ultrasound, infrasound and other physical vibrations such as molecular and atomic vibrations extends from a few femtohertz into the terahertz range and beyond.
[src:hertz/hertz] Electromagnetic radiation is often described by its frequency—the number of oscillations of the perpendicular electric and magnetic fields per second—expressed in hertz.
[src:hertz/hertz] Radio frequency radiation is usually measured in kilohertz (kHz), megahertz (MHz), or gigahertz (GHz), with the latter known as microwaves.
[src:hertz/hertz] Light is electromagnetic radiation that is even higher in frequency, and has frequencies in the range of tens of terahertz (THz)—infrared—to a few petahertz (PHz) — ultraviolet.
[src:hertz/hertz] The visible spectrum is around 400–790 THz.
[src:hertz/hertz] Electromagnetic radiation with frequencies in the low terahertz range (intermediate between those of the highest normally usable radio frequencies and long-wave infrared light) is often called terahertz radiation.
[src:hertz/hertz] Higher frequencies, such as those of X-rays and gamma rays, can be described in exahertz (EHz).
[src:hertz/hertz] For historical and practical reasons, electromagnetic radiation from infrared and above is commonly specified in terms of its wavelength in nm; X-rays and above by their photon energies in eV (keV to GeV and above).
[src:hertz/hertz] For a more detailed treatment of these frequency ranges, see *Electromagnetic spectrum*.
[src:hertz/hertz] Observations of gravitational waves are conducted in the 30–7000 Hz range by laser interferometers like LIGO, and the nanohertz (1–1000 nHz) range by pulsar timing arrays.
[src:hertz/hertz] Future space-based detectors are planned to fill in the gap, with LISA operating from 0.1–10 mHz (with some sensitivity from 10 μHz to 100 mHz), and DECIGO in the 0.1–10 Hz range.
[src:hertz/hertz] In computers, most central processing units (CPU) are labeled in terms of their clock rate expressed in megahertz (MHz) or gigahertz (GHz).
[src:hertz/hertz] This specification refers to the frequency of the CPU's master clock signal.
[src:hertz/hertz] This signal is nominally a square wave, which is an electrical voltage that switches between low and high logic levels at regular intervals.
[src:hertz/hertz] As the hertz has become the primary unit of measurement accepted by the general populace to determine the performance of a CPU, many experts have criticized this approach, which they claim is an easily manipulable benchmark.
[src:hertz/hertz] Some processors use multiple clock cycles to perform a single operation, while others can perform multiple operations in a single cycle.
[src:hertz/hertz] For personal computers, CPU clock speeds have ranged from approximately 1 MHz in the late 1970s (Atari, Commodore, Apple computers) to up to 6 GHz in IBM Power microprocessors.
[src:hertz/hertz] Various computer buses, such as the front-side bus connecting the CPU and northbridge, also operate at various frequencies in the megahertz range.
[src:hertz/hertz] Higher frequencies than the International System of Units provides prefixes for are believed to occur naturally in the frequencies of the quantum-mechanical vibrations of massive particles, although these are not directly observable and must be inferred through other phenomena.
[src:hertz/hertz] By convention, these are typically not expressed in hertz, but in terms of the equivalent energy, which is proportional to the frequency by the factor of the Planck constant.
[src:hertz/hertz] The CJK Compatibility block in Unicode contains characters for common SI units for frequency.
[src:hertz/hertz] These are intended for compatibility with East Asian character encodings, and not for use in new documents (which would be expected to use Latin letters, e.g.
